ace women occupied within this friendship community. Masonic friendship endured into the tumultuous revolutionary era, although the revolutionary leadership suppressed most of the lodges by 1794. Loiselle not only examines the place of friendship in eighteenth-century society and culture but also contributes to the history of emotions and masculinity, and the essential debate over the relationship between the Enlightenment and the French Revolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aEnlightenmentxFrance. 0aEnlightenmentzFrance. 0aFreemasonryxHistoryx18th centuryxFrance. 0aFreemasonryzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 0aMale friendshipxHistoryx18th centuryxFrance. 0aMale friendshipzFrancexHistoryy18th century. 4aEurope. 4aHistory.  amasonic lodge, eighteenth century friendship, enlightenment sociability, private sphere formation, egalitarian friendship, male relationships in history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145487540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801454875423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801454875/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles